{
  "query": "When trying to control bracken in UK heathlands, how does using herbicide alone compare to cutting, or a combination of both?",
  "relevant_summary": "According to the evidence from UK heathland studies, different bracken control methods show varying effectiveness. Using herbicide alone: Three randomized, controlled studies in the UK found that the application of herbicide reduced the biomass or cover of bracken, though one controlled study found that applying herbicide did not change the abundance of bracken (Action 1652). One systematic review found that the herbicide asulam reduced bracken abundance if applied repeatedly (Action 105). Cutting alone: Two randomized, controlled studies in the UK found that cutting bracken reduced bracken cover or biomass, while one controlled study found that cutting bracken did not decrease the abundance of bracken (Action 1653). The systematic review noted that cutting may be equally effective to herbicide application (Action 105). Combination of cutting and herbicide: Three randomized, controlled studies in the UK and Norway found that cutting and applying herbicide reduced bracken biomass or cover (Action 1654). One replicated, randomized, controlled study in the UK found that cutting bracken followed by applying herbicide increased plant species richness when compared with applying herbicide followed by cutting, suggesting the order of treatment matters (Action 1654). The evidence indicates that while all three approaches can reduce bracken, the combination method and the sequence of treatments may provide additional benefits for plant diversity.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1652",
    "1653",
    "1654",
    "105"
  ]
}

