{
  "query": "Does the effectiveness of using fences to exclude livestock from shrublands vary between different countries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Yes, the effectiveness of using fences to exclude livestock from shrublands does vary between different countries. In the UK and Germany, studies found that using fences to exclude livestock increased shrub cover, abundance, biomass, and individual heather plant biomass and height (Action 1545). Two controlled studies in Denmark and the UK found that heather presence or cover was higher in fenced areas compared to unfenced areas (Action 1545). However, one site comparison study in the USA found that using fences led to decreased cover of woody plants, while three replicated, controlled studies in the USA and the UK found that fencing either had mixed effects on shrub cover or did not alter shrub cover (Action 1545). Additional effectiveness variations were observed in grass cover responses across countries: studies in the UK and USA found that fencing led to a decline in grass cover, while studies in the USA, UK, and Finland found that fencing did not alter grass cover, and studies in the USA and UK recorded an increase in grass cover (Action 1545). For forest sections, eight studies across Argentina, Australia, Belgium, Israel, New Zealand, Spain, West Africa and the USA showed that four studies found livestock exclusion using wire fences increased understory plant biomass, species richness, density and cover, while the other four studies found mixed effects or no effect (Action 1205).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1545",
    "1205"
  ]
}

