{
  "query": "How do the effects of using cutting or mowing to mimic grazing vary between studies in Italy and Spain?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available studies, the effects of using cutting or mowing to mimic grazing show both similarities and differences between Italy and Spain. In terms of heather cover, studies in Italy found that mowing increased heather cover, while studies in Spain showed the opposite effect, with two replicated, randomized, before-and-after trials (one controlled) finding that cutting to mimic grazing reduced heather cover (Action ID: 1627). For grass cover, both countries showed similar positive effects, with studies in both Italy and Spain finding that mowing and cutting increased grass cover (Action ID: 1627). Regarding plant species diversity, one replicated, randomized, controlled, before-and-after trial in Spain found that cutting increased the number of plant species, though another replicated, randomized, before-and-after trial found that the number of plant species only increased in a minority of cases (Action ID: 1627). Tree cover was affected in Italy, where one site comparison study found a reduction in tree cover following mowing (Action ID: 1627). The studies indicate contrasting effects on heather abundance between the two countries, with Italy showing increases and Spain showing decreases, while both countries demonstrated consistent increases in grass cover from cutting/mowing treatments.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1627"
